snippet.textDisplay:
Some useful info about the psychedelic instrument and the player that you can see/hear at 3:48...

Madam Noor Zehra Kazim is a Pakistani Sagar Veena player. She is the daughter of lawyer and activist Raza Kazim who invented Sagar Veena - a stringed instrument similar to Vichitra veena and Chitra Veena.
Zehra is the only performer of Sagar Veena since its creation in 1971 and she is also the mother of noori's lead vocalist Ali Noor and guitarist Noor Hamza.
Zehra started her formal training during 1971, when she learns Rajeshwari Datta, head of the Indian Department at School of Oriental and African Studies (SOAS) teaches similar instrument in London, England. Kazim then went to Berkeley, California in US, and studies at the Ali Akbar College of Music. In Pakistan she learn under Ustad Shareef Khan Poonchwala for a few years and established herself as the only Veena player of Pakistan.

snippet.textDisplay: For those not familiar with Punjabi folklore, the song is invoking the folktale of Sohni who used to secretly cross the river Chenab every night by using a fired clay pot to keep her buoyant to go to the other side to meet her beloved Mahiwal. One day, Sohni's sister-in-law finds out about this and she replaces the fired clay pot with an unfired one, which starts dissolving in the river water that night as Sohni is crossing the river. In the song, she's urging the clay-pot to keep going because she needs to unite with Mahiwal.
